To introduce shading into a 3D game written in C# and Monogame, you can follow these steps:

1. Create shaders:
First, you need to create shader files to handle shading in your game. In Monogame, shaders are written in HLSL (High-Level Shader Language).

Create two separate files:
- VertexShader.hlsl: For vertex shader responsible for processing the 3D model's vertices and passing the data to the pixel shader.
- PixelShader.hlsl: For pixel shader responsible for calculating the final color of each pixel on the screen based on the lights, textures, and other factors.

2. Compile shaders:
To use shader files in Monogame, you need to compile them using the Monogame Pipeline Tool. Add both VertexShader.hlsl and PixelShader.hlsl to the Content folder in your Monogame project, set the Build Action property to Compile, and set their respective types: Vertex Shader and Pixel Shader.

3. Load shaders in your game:
In your 3D game project, load the compiled shaders to use them for rendering objects.

```csharp
Effect shaderEffect;
protected override void LoadContent()
{
    shaderEffect = Content.Load<Effect>("shaderEffect"); // Name of your compiled shader effect
}
```

4. Define lighting parameters:
Define necessary lighting parameters like light direction, color, and intensity. You can store these values in a Vector3 or similar object, and pass them to the shader later.

```csharp
Vector3 lightDirection = new Vector3(1, -1, 1);
Color ambientColor = Color.Gray;
Vector3 diffuseColor = Color.White.ToVector3();
float ambientIntensity = 0.1f;
```

5. Set up data for shaders:
Before drawing your 3D objects, set up your shaders with the necessary data like the World, View, and Projection matrices, as well as lighting parameters.

```csharp
shaderEffect.Parameters["World"].SetValue(worldMatrix);
shaderEffect.Parameters["View"].SetValue(viewMatrix);
shaderEffect.Parameters["Projection"].SetValue(projectionMatrix);

shaderEffect.Parameters["LightDirection"].SetValue(lightDirection);
shaderEffect.Parameters["AmbientColor"].SetValue(ambientColor.ToVector4());
shaderEffect.Parameters["DiffuseColor"].SetValue(diffuseColor);
shaderEffect.Parameters["AmbientIntensity"].SetValue(ambientIntensity);
```

6. Apply shaders when rendering:
To use the custom shading for drawing your 3D objects, apply the shader when rendering. Iterate through shader passes, set the active technique, and draw the model.

```csharp
foreach (ModelMesh mesh in model.Meshes)
{
    foreach (ModelMeshPart part in mesh.MeshParts)
    {
        part.Effect = shaderEffect;
    }

    mesh.Draw();
}
```

